    - ["as3406030", operator.contains, [asyncio.LifoQueue.__dict__,        "__repr__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __bool__, __str__, __repr__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __bool__: false for all 10 — truth-value protocol not in own __dict__.
# __str__: false for all 10 — string conversion not in own __dict__.
# __repr__: false for all 10 — repr not in own __dict__ (C-level tp_repr
#   is not exposed as a Python-level __dict__ entry).
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and explicit
#   method calls. The display protocol dunders (__bool__, __str__, __repr__)
#   are not overridden in the Python-level __dict__ of any of the 10 types.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a boolean flag via set()/clear()/is_set()
#   methods; even though the event has a logical boolean state, __bool__ is
#   not defined in asyncio.Event.__dict__ — truth-value testing of the event
#   object itself is not a supported pattern.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is encapsulated;
#   no __bool__ is defined in their __dict__ even though a semaphore with
#   value 0 could conceptually be false.
# asyncio.Task/asyncio.Future note: these types produce informative repr
#   strings at runtime (showing state, result, callbacks), but CPython
#   exposes this through the C-level tp_repr slot — not through a Python-level
#   __repr__ entry in the class __dict__. __str__ is similarly absent.
# asyncio.Queue note: qsize() is a method returning an int, but no __bool__
#   is defined in Queue.__dict__ even though an empty queue could be false.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

